John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, and this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional test scores, bolstered by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students spread across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the best level of service for both students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further study and access to universities, as well as for the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a bespoke school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought after theme in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If we talk to a man in a language he understands, we can get into his mind.
If we speak to him in his own language, we can enter his heart.”
This quote reminds us that we cannot just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of this year’s recent exams, we found that languages are at the top of the table, with the highest rates of use of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages reached the maximum grade of A.
These data, collected in the 74 schools under the SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained the maximum grade of A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This demonstrates that Scottish independent schools are favouring foreign languages as vital skills that will unquestionably serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now viewed in the same way as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and beyond.
A survey by the United Kingdom Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that, among the reasons for employers’ difficulty filling vacancies, 17% concerned a lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowing other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with a fitness for life like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit ratio of 15%.
Therefore, investing now in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Multilingual proficiency, particularly in developing countries, will give children better chances of finding relevant employment.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be a set of languages to choose from in independent schools, supported by specialized teaching staff in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them for success, whatever the future holds.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalized business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance for the future of the country.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
