"However, we do not see any corresponding U.S. response," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way we can proceed with our disarmament first.”
While Ri has recycled well-known North Korean grievances about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it takes gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in that they do not liminally reject unilateral denuclearization, in contrast to Pyongyang’s previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump offered security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on “denuclearization first” and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, opposing even the “declaration of the end of the war,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of sanctions is aggravating our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the stakeholder in this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this stalemate."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that steering North Korea’s rockets into U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Bad President” Trump called Kim the “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but said much remained to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea was denuclearized.
