The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their alteration in the laboratory.
These cells, which can “see” a protein common to many cancers, are then injected back into the body.
An experimental vaccine is producing promising results in patients with a range of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells, saw her ovarian cancer go away for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient and changing them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2. These cells are then injected back into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results suggest we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of various types of cancers," including those of the breast, ovary, lungs and also the colorectals, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach that involves removing immune cells from patients and “teaching them” to attack cancer cells worked in treating a type of leukemia.
