National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research is underway on a property in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and fruit bats, as well as long-eared browns and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations scattered throughout the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and by volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all recordings will assess the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A map of the habitat will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviors on a territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as meadow breeding, as well as how best to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined considerably over the past century.
These animals are threatened by the construction and development work that affects the dormitories and makes the habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning are also a threat, along with fly-killing papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given your night hunting habits, your ears are more useful than your eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo tracking technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts who regularly conduct studies, dorm inspections, and sometimes rescues.
He also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats, at the Threave property in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten Scottish bat species.
The property’s director, David Thompson, says it’s the ideal territory for them.
“Here in Threate we have an excellent area for bats,” he said.
"We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and all this good habitat.
However, there’s still a lot about bats that we don’t know, so the work we’ve done here and on the other properties will help us know more about what they need to flourish.”
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance on the properties, as the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dormitory could lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dormitories.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we simply don’t know how their populations are avenging.”
