He moved to the Stadium of Light this summer after guiding St. Mirren on their return to the Scottish First Division last season.
“I wanted to represent my country as a player.
But I only got a B internationalization," Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportsound programme.
“I grew up watching Scotland play in Hampden with my father and these are some of my best memories.
But this opportunity will only arise if he succeeds in managing clubs.”
Ross' predecessors as coach of Sunderland include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic coach says he was not afraid to succeed such established names at such a large club after rejecting invitations from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
“For me, for now, success comes down to ‘Can I bring the club back to the Premier League?’
“Given the structure and facilities of the club, their place is undoubtedly in the Premier League,” he said.
"It will not be easy to bring the club back, but I will only consider that I was successful here when I achieve that goal."
Ross’s coaching career is only three years old, after a stint as an assistant coach for Dumbarton and 15 months on the Hearts technical team.
He then helped Alloa recover from the descent to the third division and led St. Mirren from the threat of demotion to the title of champion the following season.
Ross says he feels more comfortable now than he has ever felt during his playing career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St. Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
Taking care of Alloa "was a real crossroads," he recalls.
“I’ve always seen myself more in the role of coach than in the role of player.
It seems strange because it went well, I made a living as a player and I had some high moments in my career.
But playing can be very hard.
We face many challenges every week.
I still face them in terms of the stress and pressures of the position, but I feel very good as a coach.
I’ve always wanted to train and now that I do, I feel more comfortable than I’ve ever felt throughout my adult life.”
