Updated Red Tide Information: Concentrations Fall in Pinellas, Manatee, and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in concentrations of Red Tide in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of lower spot proliferation were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Tide patch extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also spotted in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations were recorded along or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations along or off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom to high concentrations along or off the coast of Le County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwestern region of Florida.
